cluster_description: High, near-continuous short herbaceous cover (~94%), negligible shrubs and trees, very low built cover and high NDVI. Consistent with intensively managed short turf/amenity lawns (e.g., sports turf, mown park lawns).
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots are characterised by a continuous, low-stature sward dominated by short mown grass, producing an open herbaceous layer with limited vertical structural complexity. Vegetation shows evidence of regular mowing and high formal maintenance, yielding a uniform, homogenous short-turf cover across the plot. Visibility from the plots extends beyond 30 m to a distant tree line, indicating an expansive, unobstructed grassland surface with woody vegetation confined to the margins.

cluster_description: Very high NDVI with dominant large-tree canopy (~39% mean large-tree cover), modest understory of small trees and shrubs and low built cover. Typical of closed or mature urban woodland or remnant tree stands.
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots assigned to the mature large‑tree canopy/woodland category are dominated by a closed tree canopy with multiple mature trunks and a vertically structured vegetation profile. Understorey layers are commonly dense, comprising shrubs and small trees, and ground surfaces frequently show leaf litter or bare soil. Visibility within plots is generally limited, ranging from short (<10 m) to medium (10–30 m) distances. Most plots lack visible built infrastructure (buildings, roads, paved elements) and exhibit low to very low maintenance intensity (semi‑wild to wild condition); a minority contain narrow or informal earth paths or occasional mown tracks. There was no consistent evidence of litter, parked vehicles or people within the plots.

cluster_description: Very high herbaceous cover (~69%), very low shrub and tree cover and low built cover; high NDVI consistent with expansive, open grassland areas (meadow or amenity grassland).
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots were characterized by continuous tall-herbaceous vegetation forming an open meadow, with trees limited to a discrete background line. No built structures, roads, vehicles or people were visible and no formal or informal paths traversed the plots. Maintenance intensity was low (semi‑wild) with no evidence of mowing and minimal visual clutter. Visibility extended to medium distances (10–30 m), providing spatial depth across the plots.

cluster_description: Mixed canopy of mature trees over open grass: substantial herb layer (~48%) combined with a notable large-tree component (~17%), moderate small-tree and shrub fractions and low built cover. Typical of parkland with mature trees and grassy understory.
habitat_description_from_photos: Selected plots are characterized by continuous expanses of short, recently mown grass forming an open herbaceous sward with long visibility (>30 m). Mature trees occur at plot margins and produce a scattered canopy over the grassy matrix, while shrubs occupy some peripheral zones and create a woody boundary to the open area. Vegetation structure therefore reflects an open parkland configuration: a dominant grassy matrix with interspersed large-tree elements and localized shrub patches.

cluster_description: Moderate herb cover (~38%) with a moderate component of large trees (~20%), modest small-tree and shrub cover and intermediate built cover (~29%). Suggestive of parkland or greenspace with scattered/patchy mature trees over grass (less continuous tree canopy than 'parkland — mature trees over grass').
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots are characterized by open grassy swards with scattered mature trees forming an open canopy and an open understorey of short, regularly mown turf. Shrub cover is generally low or confined to plot margins in some plots. Occasional pedestrian access (paved and narrow informal earth tracks) bisects plots. Maintenance intensity varies across plots, with recent mowing evident in several cases and visibility distances typically in the medium range (≈10–30 m).

cluster_description: Mixed herb-shrub-small-tree profile (herb ~37%, shrub ~12%, small trees ~10%, large trees ~10%) with moderate built cover (~30%) and intermediate NDVI. Suggests heterogeneous shrub–tree mosaic or young/secondary scrub-woodland interspersed with some impervious features.
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots assigned to the shrub–small-tree mosaic / young scrub‑woodland type are characterized by a heterogeneous vegetation structure in which grassy openings are interspersed with shrubs and scattered trees. The grassy component and patches of shrub cover occur alongside small trees, producing a patchy, mosaic appearance; some plots include a small water body with floating vegetation. Visibility within plots is moderate (approximately 10–30 m), and plots show evidence of moderate management (recent mowing) consistent with a semi‑managed, young scrub–woodland mosaic.

cluster_description: Moderate herb cover (~46%) combined with low tree/shrub cover and relatively high built cover (~39%) and mid-range NDVI. Representative of residential greenspace or small urban plots with grass and occasional trees/vegetation fragments amidst built fabric.
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots are characterized by extensive cover of short, regularly mown grass forming open grassy areas with scattered trees and occasional shrubs. Trees are often mature with an open understorey, creating a discontinuous canopy over predominantly herbaceous groundcover. Vegetation condition in the plots is commonly moderate to high maintenance, with recent mowing evident, and visibility across the plots is typically medium (approximately 10–30 m).

cluster_description: Very low NDVI and sparse vegetation across all strata (herb ~13%, shrubs and trees <3–4%) with very high built cover (~79%). Characteristic of largely impervious areas (roads, car parks, dense built-up infrastructure) with minimal vegetation.
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots are dominated by continuous impervious groundcover (extensive paved surfaces associated with vehicular access and parking), with negligible vegetative cover across strata. When vegetation occurs it is limited and peripheral (small patches or linear planting at edges); overall plots exhibit long sightlines and low structural vegetation complexity. Surface condition is generally intact and reflects consolidated hard-standing rather than permeable or vegetated substrates.

cluster_description: Intermediate-to-low NDVI with moderate herb (~28%) and relatively high built cover (~53%), low-to-moderate woody cover. Suggestive of urban fabric dominated by impervious surfaces but containing vegetated fragments (gardens, planted verges) — more built-dominated than other clusters.
habitat_description_from_photos: Plots are dominated by hardstanding (paved surfaces, roads and parking areas) with small, discrete vegetated fragments. Vegetation within plots occurs primarily as short mown grass lawns, shrub-dominated patches and occasional tall-herb stands or tree canopies with open understories; connectivity of vegetation is limited and cover is often sparse or confined to edges and narrow strips alongside paths. Maintenance intensity and mowing evidence vary across plots (from very low/semi‑wild to moderate or formally maintained), and vegetated fragments are typically adjoined or bounded by residential buildings and road infrastructure. Visibility distances are generally medium (≈10–30 m), yielding modest perceived depth across plots.
